17. This identification constitutes one of the most serious displacement problems in Blake’s Faerie Queene procession. Though Arthegall is present, even important, in Book IV, he is really more central to Book V. Of the trappings given Arthegall by Blake, the one actually described by Spenser is the prophesied crown (see III, iii, 29);


A 17 Arthegall

otherwise, Spenser never really describes Arthegall’s person, only his armor, shield and helmet with the "couchant hound" (III, ii, 25). He is first introduced as the vision in Britomart’s father’s mirror in Book III. It is said that he is "portly" (III, ii, 24) and that he has a "lovely face," "tempered with sternesse and stout maiestie" (IV, vi, 26). These characteristics appear sufficiently evident in Blake’s figure to identify him as Arthegall; moreover, such an identification is practically a necessity. Arthur, never a titular character, and present in all Books, establishes his most vivid presence, perhaps, in Book V. Thus, it is he who takes the fifth prominent position (21) in the painting, thereby displacing Arthegall from the Book that bears his name. Consequently, Arthegall is advanced to the fourth position of prominence, where he can be joined with Britomart and also hailed by Arthur. It is also unlikely that Arthegall’s "squire," Talus (20), would be present without his master. Arthegall’s positioning, however, completely displaces the titular firgures of Book IV, Cambell and Triamond. Perhaps Blake felt that although these characters are emblematic of friendship, their actual roles in The Faerie Queene are too insignificant (they are only really important to IV, ii and IV, iii) to justify giving them such a prominent position.
